Lessions, that can be learned today from the Cuban crisis
“Thirteen Days” (“Thirteen Days”), a new film about the Cuban crisis, is set to start in cinemas of numerous countries soon.
Everyone should watch this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – especially with regard to the controversies surrounding a US-American national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called his closest advisors to the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a stationing of atomic weapons on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and the decisions that were not made, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during these days.
Recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government in Harvard launched a discussion round that should discuss the film as well as the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this round included, among others: Robert McNamara, the defense minister under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter of Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a Harvard professor of history who wrote a book on the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a Harvard professor of political science who, thirty years ago, presented a classic study on the Cuban crisis, the work "Essence of Decision".
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was also present.
Although the filmic treatment of the subject was criticized in various points, the discussion participants agreed that the film portrays the problems and pressure with which President Kennedy was confronted exactly as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn from the Cuban crisis today?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in the case of a crisis, yet it is solely the President who ultimately has to bear the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – both civil and military – wanted to attack Cuba at the time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be shown, which were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; furthermore, the communication channels must be kept open.
To push an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open, which enable one to understand the opponent's situation, could prove disastrous.
· The US relies on allies.
Kennedy acted that way because NATO, other allies, and world opinion had supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life and death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into a decision.
The fact that a week passed in which all the factors involved were thoroughly examined and weighed was crucial to the outcome.
But would such a time frame for deliberations even exist in today's era of mass media?
Robert McNamara stressed the need to put oneself in the position of the opponent.
In one of the scenes criticized by many in the film, McNamara explains to an aggressive Admiral that the naval blockade Kennedy had imposed on Cuba was above all intended to send a signal to Soviet leader Khrushchev of Kennedy's intentions, and not as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more lax?
After all, the USA had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station rockets on Cuba merely reflected this policy.
However, Kennedy expressed himself anxiously with regard to the consequences a stationing of Soviet rockets on Cuba would have brought with itself with regard to Berlin.
The pressure of atomic weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
"In the end, the Berlin crisis was resolved through the results of the Cuban crisis," claims the historian Ernest May.
"It will soon be too late," was a widely disseminated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
His advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the rockets – as they assumed – were on their way to Cuba by sea.
About an 180,000 man strong US troop was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a blitz-bombardement, which in its scope would have been larger than NATO's attack in Kosovo sixty years later.
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He posed Castro the following three questions:
1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
Castro replied: “I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used."
I knew that this would lead to the annihilation of Cuba.”
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were prepared to have Cuba go up in smoke, so that their country would become a martyr in the fight for world revolution!
An invasion would have had the consequence of the death of 80 million US Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy government did not possess sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is of the firm conviction that an invasion would "undoubtedly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack on the USA.
Chruschtschows control over the Soviet military on Cuba was limited, however: despite explicitly contrary instructions from the chairman, U2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were shot at.
A difficult question to answer, which did not arise during the debate at Harvard, is the following: What would have happened if it was not Chruschtschow, who has distinguished himself during the crisis by a reasonable behavior, but an opponent of the type of Saddam Husseins, Kim Jong Ils or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of atomic weapons, this danger could one day become a reality.
The current discussions on limited missile defense and the threat of atomic blackmail by rogue states should be led in the light of this terrible, but by all means realistic thought.
Harvard has placed a new web site on the Internet, on which the essential documents about the Cuban crisis as well as about the current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org .
